Q1. 178, 200, 146, 174, 124, 166, 132, 134, 140, 182  

- All of them are even.  
- All of them are composite (no prime in the list).  
- Every value is ≥ 120 and ≤ 200.  
- Mean ≈ 158.6, median = 153, range = 200 – 124 = 76.  
- None is a perfect square, cube, or power of 2.  
- Digit-sum of each number is even.  
- Taken mod 10 they all finish in 0, 2, 4, 6 or 8 (which is just the “even” observation again).  
- No obvious arithmetic or geometric pattern; the set is simply a clump of even integers in the 120-to-200 band.

Q2. 103, 101, 197, 151, 127, 137, 179, 199, 191, 109  

- Every one of them is an odd number.  
- Every one of them is prime.  
- All are ≥ 101 and ≤ 199.  
- They are exactly the ten primes that lie between 100 and 200 inclusive.  
- Mean ≈ 159.3, median = 154, range = 199 – 101 = 98.  
- None is divisible by 3, 5, 7, 11… (they are primes).  
- Digit-sum is odd for each (because the numbers themselves are odd).  
- Collectively they are the “hundred-primes” – the complete list of primes in the second century. [end of text]


